Why "Engrish" is so widespread throughout Asia
Translation errors are widespread in Japan and throughout Asia.
The Engrish.com website is a treasure trove for these bizarre mistakes in English.
Photo by Flickr user Andrew.
The reasons for the wide spread of translation errors are manifold.
To translate, you need two important skills: passive language skills to understand the source text and provide active language skills to transfer it to the target language.
The latter requires active control of the target language - something that is the case with native speakers. generally, the conviction is that translators in the target language - not in the original language - should be native speakers.
For example, a French native speaker should translate from English into French - not from French into English.
Photo by Flickr user Karl Baron.
Many Japanese companies employ no staff with English as their native language, who could translate translations into English. this may be due to a lack of understanding of translation, cost reasons or the relatively low number of English native speakers that learn Japanese.
Some companies that do not have foreign employees can nevertheless produce translations in-house. then the Japanese employee, whose English knowledge is valued as the best, becomes a translator - no matter how good or bad his language skills really are.
Photo by Flickr user Karl Baron.
Mechanical translations are also widespread - often with funny results.
The confused and enigmatic sentences resulting from machine translation show that this technique cannot replace a human translator for a long time. this is especially true for some languages.
Some of the strangest British formulations in Japan, including the enigmatic imprints that often decorate T-shirts or bags, are only used for stylistic reasons - not to be read or even understood.
Photo by Flickr user Joseph Brent.
Translation errors may be acceptable or at least harmless as jewellery, but from large companies or from the government, which have the means to ensure higher standards, more careful translations can be expected.
In the future, the city of Kyoto will hopefully use a more serious source for its translation.
