This is precisely the question of the two young Colombian activists Leonardo Párraga from the Foundation BogotArt and Cristian Palacios from the Young-Youth Foundation and inspired them to the campaign Carta por la cumliación (letters to reconciliation), encouraging young people to write letters to guerrilla fighters.
Only recently, their country was the scene of a historic event and they wanted to contribute to it: after years of negotiations, the Colombian government closed a peace treaty with the guerrilla war FARC (German: Revolutionary Armed Forces), which forms the final point of the longest armed conflict in Latin America.
The signing of the Peace Treaty was considered to be so significant that the Colombian president José Manuel Santos received the Nobel Peace Prize for his merits.
However, before the Colombians there is still a long way to speak of a real reconciliation and peace.
Guerrillas, who lived in illegal camps for many years, were exposed to a rhetoric of war, and around the clock had their weapons in their hands, now have to integrate themselves into the lives of civilians.
The Colombian society, which has become accustomed to life in constant fear and in some cases deep hatred of guerrilla fighters, must now take them into their ranks and support them in building up a new life.
Leonardo and Cristian were convinced that the young Colombians had to join together and help with the integration process.
And that's exactly what they did: up to now thousands of young people have already written letters - love messages to former guerrilla fighters to welcome them back to society.
The aim of the campaign is 6900 letters - one for every guerrilla fighter who is to be handed over personally.
Valentine's Day as inspiration for the campaign
The idea for the letters to reconciliation was created on the World Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates, which took place in Bogotá in February 2017. Leonardo and Cristian had the opportunity to talk briefly with Kailash Satyarthi, who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2014.
He explained that we write thousands of love letters to the people we love on Valentine's Day, but forget those who need them much more.
He plans to share his love with people this year, who needed most of them.
So the plan was to write letters full of hope and support for former FARC soldiers who will now find their place in society and build up a new life. "the letters will show that Colombian society is ready to make the discourse of war history a common history of peace."
To date, more than 2000 letters have been collected during the campaign.
The initiative is represented in all major cities in Colombia such as Cali, Manicales, Medellín, Barranquilla and Bogotá.
