They even suggest well thought out scientific and social arguments in front of me why I should be a feminist and why we should generally be all feminist * inside.
For example, women nowadays still earn less money than men despite equal education.
That women are still under strict observation when it comes to what they are allowed to do with their body.
Violence against women is a global epidemic.
Or that cultural and social norms ensure that women sooner or later meet a glass ceiling in various areas of life, and that discrimination on the basis of sex is still moving across the many different countries and faiths.
All of this is aware of me and well-known.
I am convinced of it and I suffer double and triple among them.
I am a black woman.
And yet: when I come to speak on skin color, on racism, black Cis women, black women in the LGBTIQ community or on black women from the Diaspora; if I mention how we have always been abused under racial segregation and discrimination; if I mention the way we have been abused physically, mentally and verbally, both in and outside the feminist movement, many white feminists have been silent.
But they all agree that women - all women - should come together to "raise their voices and" singing Kumbaya, my Lord "in order to achieve equal rights (some) of women.
But they do not want to talk about the fact that in addition to sexualized violence, there is an institutionalised form of racist motivated violence, which we are subjected to black women in two ways.
Or that black women and women of other ethnicities and places of origin earn less than white men and women.
That black girls and girls with a migration background often are referred to the school as white girls, due to obvious integration problems.
Or that women in black spheres and women with a migration background are exposed to a higher risk of suffering domestic violence and violence in partnership than white women.
On the one hand I want all women, all men and all men of any skin color to have the same rights; on the other hand, I can't join a movement in whose center the white woman stands, who refuses to take into account injustice in her mind, which relate both to gender and to the skin color of a person.
I am exhausted and will no longer fight for my affiliation in a white-feminist-oriented sphere that has repeatedly rejected me and countless other black women.
"" "" "" "am I not a woman?" "" "and I also refuse to maintain an ideology in which the black woman is an unmended and marginalized being in historical terms." ""
