The trial against Al-Maamari, Al-Haj and Al-Abri took place before the Court in Maskat on 26 September 2016.
The Tribunal sentenced the three journalists to prison terms and also ordered the final closure of the newspaper.
Al-Maamari and Al-Haj were both condemned by interference of the public order, "misuse of the Internet," and "undermining the state of the state."
In addition, Al-Haj was found guilty of the violation of a ban on publication and of slander.
Al-Maamari and Al-Haj were sentenced to three years of imprisonment and fines of 3,000 omanic Rial (7800 US dollars). in addition, a one-year ban was imposed on the two journalists.
Al-Abri was sentenced to a year prison and a fine of 1000 Rial (2600 US dollars) after he was found guilty of using "an information network for spreading material that could pose a threat to public order."
For Al-Abri, a bail was set in the amount of 5000 omanic Rial (13,000 US dollars) and was released on 22 August 2016 prior to the pronouncement of the sentence.
The Appeals Court acquitted Al-Abri in a hearing on 26 December 2016, but sentenced Al-Haj to a year and Al-Maamari for six months in prison.
Al-Maamari was released on 10 April 2017 after his six-month jail sentence from the Central Prison in Maskat. al-Haj remains in prison, where he served his first prison sentence.
The Appeals Court also revoked the decision of the Ministry of Information to close the Azamn paper.
Despite the decision of the Court to allow Azamn to resume, the newspaper still faces attacks by the omanic government.
On 8 January, the Minister of Information issued a statement with which the closure of Azamn was extended by three months.
On 8 May 2017, the Minister of Information personally signed a further instruction in which the closure of Azamn was extended by three additional months, and with what the minister once again opposed the decision of the Appeals Court to allow the publication of the newspaper again.
The ongoing closure of Azamn and the attacks on journalists of the newspaper are not the only cases in which in recent times press freedom has been violated.
Other violations include, for example, the closure of the website of the independent magazine Mowatin and the exercise of pressure on Albalad, the country's first independent online newspaper to stop its operation.
Due to the ongoing closure of Azamn and the arrest of the journalist Al-Haj, the impression that the authorities are still unwilling to put an end to the extensive violation of press freedom.
The Gulf Centre for Human Rights (Gulf Centre for Human Rights, GCHR) calls on the authorities to:
1. release Yousef Al-Haj immediately and unconditionally;
2. to create a safe environment for the newspaper Azamn, so that their journalists can follow their work;
3. to protect the freedom of the press in the country and
4. in all circumstances, human rights defenders and journalists in Oman have unhindered their legitimate human rights work and can exercise without fear of retaliation, including judicial chicanes.
