Medical research in Africa: opportunities and misunderstandings
Ranjit Warrier 2016 in Zambia, picture takes place with his consent
Medical research in Africa is rarely mentioned in the media or not at all. it is a growing area addressing one of the most pressing needs of the continent.
There are two reasons for the need for medical research carried out locally: on the one hand, there are many medicines and vaccines that cover the special medical need on the African continent.
Diseases such as AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria have far more serious effects than elsewhere in the poorest countries of Africa, and lack of investment in research on these diseases by the pharmaceutical companies is a major problem.
Second, research carried out by African scientists is helping to build up their own research capacities in Africa. a greater role in science and technology can only be conducive to the economic growth of the continent.
Dr. Ranjit Warrier is Director of the Centre for the Research of Infectious Disease Research in Zambia (Centre for Infectious Disease Research in Zambia, CIDRZ).
In the 1990s he grew up in Lusaka, Zambia, just when the AIDS epidemic showed serious consequences for national health.
He left Zambia for a study in the United States, initially in Louisiana, later in Indiana.
As a postdoc at the University of Pennsylvania he researched the HIV virus itself before deciding to go back home in order to support the Samba health system.
With Global Voices, Dr. Warrier discussed the future of medical research in Zambia and about misunderstandings of the media about this research.
(disclaimer: Dr. Warrier talks as a private person).
Global Voices (GV): what is your research topic?
Ranjit Warrier RW: at the moment the focus of my work is on the application of research results. I support the Sambian National Programme for antiretroviral therapy (ART) with laboratory tests.
In addition, I am currently starting a research programme for the development of molecular diagnostic tests for HIV, TB and other relevant pathogens.
CC: what do you think are the most important current scientific topics in your country and in general in Africa?
How do they differ from those in Western countries?
RW: there is no basic research here. we only use solutions that have been developed elsewhere.
This has to change, otherwise we will always remain the recipients instead of being themselves creators.
The solutions we get are often not well used in our environment, and sometimes it is even impossible to use them here.
CC: where does the funding and support come from?
Is it sufficient?
How easy or difficult is it to find suitable scientists for the projects?
RW: from the USA and Europe.
The projects are promoted in different ways.
It is difficult to find people who want to come back or move here, because financing and development chances are better in other countries.
CC: what is the research infrastructure?
What obstacles are there in your routine research work that you did not have before?
RW: the basic infrastructure does not meet the standards in developed countries. it costs a lot of money to have a continuous supply of electricity, water and internet.
Laboratory material is expensive and it takes months to import it from other countries.
CC: what is the opinion of the public about science and scientists in Africa?
RW: there is already interest, but only a very limited understanding of scientific methods.
I would suggest that critical thinking and scientific methods should be taught in schools to improve the situation.
CC: how big is your opinion on the potential of scientific research in Africa, what should it concentrate on, and how can we support the development?
RW: the potential is amazing.
I have seen great students of all ages.
There is a need for special scientific training, starting at any age.
Social sciences, computer science, big data, space exploration, healthcare (non-transferable and infectious diseases) and the efficiency of traditional medicine will benefit greatly.
CC: can you describe the pros and cons of life as a scientist in Africa compared to Western countries, based on your experience?
RW: often it is the limited speed to do things, and the difficult access to scientific expertise that poses challenges here.
