One night in the autumn of 1994, the occupation of Afghanistan began by the Taliban.
Two years earlier, a terrible civil war broke out between the various Mujahedin groups that had defeated the short-lived pro-Soviet government. Afghanistan has become a country of terror and despair.
Exactly at that time, Asharaf Barati, a 13-year-old boy belonging to the Ethnic Group of Hazara, spent the last time together with his family at dinner in the province of Ghazni in Central Afghanistan.
Even if his mother didn't say it that way, she knew that she would not see her son for a long time - maybe even more.
In the morning, the boy should break.
His uncle would pick him up and bring him to the tugs.
The city of Ghazni in Afghanistan.
Photo from the ISAF headquarter Public Affairs Office.
Members of the Provincial Reconstruction Teams of the province of Ghazni visited the town of Ghazni, located in the Province of the same name, on 18 April 2010.
(joint Combat Camera Afghanistan; photo by Technical Serge James May).
New Products for CC-2.0
Abdul Ali Mazari, leader of the Hezb-e-Wahdat, dominated by Hazara, had just been murdered by the Taliban and many hazards suddenly felt vulnerable.
The Taliban, known for their hatred of the Hazara, came closer and closer.
Many Hazara left the country in the direction of Pakistan or Iran.
A few days after his escape, Asharaf found himself in Pakistan.
For a few years he worked in a coal mine. the work was difficult and made him ill.
Then he took what was left of his little reward and went to Iran. once again he found himself in a foreign country together with other refugees and dragged sacks with mortar that were heavier than he himself, in order to earn his living.
Back then, as today, the life of Afghan refugees in Iran was marked by misery and exploitation.
"" "" "" "it was really tough," "" "remembered Asharaf in an interview with Global Voices." "" "we (Afghan refugees) lived in an empty building on the building site, on which we worked." ""
There was no service and no heating. we hung nylon in front of the open windows to prevent us from freezing at night. "
After four years, Asharaf dismissed his life without documents in Iran and was ready for the journey to Europe.
During the dangerous crossing on the sea, he suffered shipwreck and stranded on a small, uninhabited Greek island.
After the Greek authorities rejected his asylum application, Asharaf came to Italy in 2002.
Some time, Asharaf was homeless, ran alone through the streets of Rome, slept in parks and went to a church that distributed food to aid needy twice a day.
It is true that due to relatively high ratings, Italy is a second chance for rejected asylum seekers. however, it is also true that the conditions that asylum seekers find in the country are catastrophic.
The Civil Liberties Union for Europe writes, "the system" suffers from a general lack of transparency.
"" "the large majority of asylum seekers are accommodated in the more than 3000" "" "special reception centres" "". "these are improvised facilities in the hands of unqualified and unprepared personnel." "" "" ""
According to Italian law, asylum seekers can only be assigned to an admission centre if they have officially submitted an application for asylum, which can still withdraw for months after the registration of the asylum application.
Until then, people who have no money for accommodation are either dependent on the hospitality of friends or have to sleep on the street.
And so did Asharaf.
But his immortal will helped Asharaf to free himself from these conditions.
After several years of working in the construction industry, Asharaf put his total savings in the establishment of a hostel in Venice.
This was so good that after a while, he opened a second hostel and a fast snack bar.
Asharaf Baratis success story is now the theme of the documentary "Behind Venice Luxury - a Hazara in Italy" (German: "after Venetian luxury - a Hazara in Italy") by the director Amin Wahidi.
In 2017, the film won the Venice City Award, which was awarded for the 24th time in 2017.
Asharaf Barati before the "Casa Fiori," one of his hostels in Venice.
Photo by Basir Ahang.
Use with kind permission.
The conditions for entrepreneurs in Italy - especially for non-Italians - are very difficult.
A lot of bureaucracy, high taxes and conditions for loans are just some of the obstacles.
According to unofficial estimates, about 20,000 Afghans live in Italy.
For many of them, the country is a transitional solution on the road to other European countries.
In recent years, several Afghan-powered companies, including tailor shops, travel agencies, hotels and restaurants have emerged.
Some Afghan restaurants were praised even in the Italian press for their excellent cuisine.
In Venice, Hamed Ahmadi had the idea for his Restaurant Oriental Experience, where the waiters and kitchen staff are mostly refugees from different parts of the world.
The menu of the restaurant tells the story of their trip to Italy by the various Afghan, Iraqi, Turkish and Greek dishes.
The Afghan entrepreneur Ali Khan Qalandari opened in Padua the restaurant peace & amp; Spice and also behind the pizzeria Kabulogna in Bologna and a sushi restaurant in Rome are also Afghans.
But Asharafs targets extend far beyond the Italian hospitality industry and retailers and aim to return to the country he had forced to leave as a teenager.
"where there is a risk, there are also possibilities," says Asharaf with a smile. "I want to invest in Afghanistan.
I have never forgotten my country and I can't live happily when I know that my people are suffering.
I plan a project for farmers from the poorest provinces of the country, especially for women.
"" "they represent half of society and have to get the same possibilities as everyone else." "" "" ""
"" "Asharaf also plans plans for the opening of a factory in Kabul, where people can learn packaging and preservation techniques." "" "so they can sell their harvest surpluses on the market and improve their financial situation," "" "he says." ""
The development of the successful entrepreneur was a journey through uncertainty and doubt, but in the end there is stability and prosperity.
Asharaf has made this journey himself. now he wants to help other Afghans on this path.
